### COMMIT and ROLLBACK

COMMIT and ROLLBACK are transaction control statements that finalize or undo changes made during a transaction.

---

### COMMIT

COMMIT makes all changes in the current transaction permanent and visible to other users:

```sql
BEGIN TRANSACTION;
DELETE FROM temp_data;
INSERT INTO audit_log (action) VALUES ('Data purge completed');
COMMIT;
```

### ROLLBACK

ROLLBACK undoes all changes made since the BEGIN TRANSACTION (or since a savepoint):

```sql
BEGIN TRANSACTION;
DELETE FROM employees WHERE id = 100;
-- Oops, wrong employee!
ROLLBACK;  -- Employee is restored
```

### Auto-Commit Mode

By default, most database clients operate in auto-commit mode where each statement is its own transaction:

```sql
-- Each statement is auto-committed
INSERT INTO log VALUES ('Event 1');  -- Auto-committed
INSERT INTO log VALUES ('Event 2');  -- Auto-committed
```

### SAVEPOINT and Partial Rollback

Savepoints allow partial rollback within a transaction:

```sql
BEGIN TRANSACTION;

UPDATE products SET price = price * 1.1 WHERE category = 'Electronics';
SAVEPOINT electronics_updated;

UPDATE products SET price = price * 1.2 WHERE category = 'Clothing';

-- Roll back only the clothing update
ROLLBACK TO SAVEPOINT electronics_updated;

COMMIT;  -- Only Electronics prices are changed
```

### Error Handling

```sql
BEGIN TRY
    BEGIN TRANSACTION;
        UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;
        UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2;
    COMMIT;
END TRY
BEGIN CATCH
    ROLLBACK;
    SELECT ERROR_MESSAGE() AS error;
END CATCH;
```

> **Key Point:** Always close your transactions with COMMIT or ROLLBACK to release database resources. Unclosed transactions can cause blocking and deadlocks.

codeExample:
BEGIN TRANSACTION;

UPDATE products SET stock = stock - 5 WHERE id = 42;

IF @@ROWCOUNT = 0
    ROLLBACK;
ELSE
    COMMIT;
